You're thermometer was not measuring the temperature of the gasoline. Once a liquid gets to it's boiling point, it doesn't get hotter (excluding superheated liquids). Boiling is when the vapor pressure reaches ambient pressure. Heat going in raises the temperature until it get's to the boiling point, past that the heat is used to convert the liquid into a has (heat of vaporization).

The boiling point of gasoline is around 85 deg C (at 1 Atm pressure), not ~160 deg C. I suspect the thermometer was reading the IR coming through the clear gasoline from the pot/hotplate.

Autoignition temp for gasoline (vapor) is close to 280 deg C.

The ignition temperature of gasoline is 280°C (536°F). However, flammable liquids cannot ignite in their liquid state. They have to become vapor (gaseous) before they can ignite. So the gasoline vapors have to reach 280°C before they will ignite. Of course, the vapors also require sufficient oxygen for ignition. Even though your liquid gasoline got very hot, either the vapor cooled too much during transition, or the heat and vapors were crowding the oxygen out.

Pyrex lab glassware is borosilicate glass, Pyrex kitchenware from before some time in the 90s is borosilicate glass, but modern Pyrex kitchenware in the US is regular tempered glass. Ignition temperature of gasoline is around 232 degrees Celsius (~495 F)...boiling point is around 35 degrees Celsius (~95 F).  You could maybe get gas to ignite if you threw a small amount into an oven heated to 500F (High), but it's difficult to say given the way the gas and heat are dispersed over large volumes.  If you put the gas in the oven and heated it, it would likely all boil off into vapor before it ignited, but if the oven was well sealed the vapor that is trapped would likely ignite once the oven hit ~495F.

Gasoline from a pump has bits of debris in it (all pumps do, not like giant chunks, but small bits of dirt do get in there) That debris is why you saw the darkening color. It was burning. That debris was also allowing for nucleation points, and that is what was causing the bubbles. Also the glas shattered from thermal shock. Gold liquid on hot glass. You can't heat something (liquid) higher than its boiling point. The moment it gets hotter than its boiling point it will just go into gas state.
The only reason the gasoline was getting hotter, is that gasoline is a mixture of hydrocarbon chains of different length. The shorter the chain, the lower the boiling point.
The low length hydrocarbon chains were boiling off and the chains with a longer length have a higher boiling point -> that the reason the gasoline got hotter.
The reason why you saw an oily substance near the end of your boiling, is because long hydrocarbon chains are exactly that: oil. Gasoline is basically a very light oil.
